- Accounting: Logs sent from AP/Switch or Router to AAA Server (start/stop records)

4. Pick any app you use daily (Instagram, Paytm, or Flipkart) and write a paragraph explaining how AAA concepts could be applied to secure user logins and actions within that app.<br><br><em><strong>Hint:</strong> Think about what happens when you log in, what features you are allowed to use, and how your actions might be tracked for security or billing.</em>
=>When using Paytm for payments or recharges, Authentication occurs during login with phone number + OTP/PIN/biometrics to verify user identity. Authorization then applies: a verified user can access wallet balance, send money, or book tickets, but features like high-value transfers require additional KYC checks or limits based on account tier. Accounting tracks all transactions, login attempts, and session details for fraud detection, dispute resolution, compliance with financial regulations, and generating statements—ensuring actions are logged immutably for security audits. This layered AAA approach protects sensitive financial data while enabling seamless user experience.

5. Use ChatGPT or any AI tool to generate a sample AAA policy for a college WiFi network that restricts access to students only, allows certain websites, and logs all access attempts. Paste the generated policy and briefly explain how each AAA function is addressed.
=>Policy Name: CollegeWiFi_StudentAccess
Scope: Campus Wireless Network

Authentication: All users must authenticate via 802.1X/EAP with valid student email and password against the central directory (e.g., Active Directory). Guest accounts denied. Failed attempts (after 3 tries) trigger temporary MAC block.
Authorization: Authenticated students granted access to internet with bandwidth caps (5 Mbps). Allow academic sites (edu domains, library proxies) and essential services (email, LMS). Block social media/gaming during lecture hours via time-based ACLs. Role-based: Faculty get higher bandwidth and full access.
Accounting: Log all login/logout times, IP assignments, data usage, and accessed domains. Store logs for 90 days. Generate daily reports for security team; alert on suspicious patterns (e.g., multiple failed logins or unusual data spikes).
